		<dc:title id="title">Short Fiction</dc:title>
		<meta property="file-as" refines="#title">Short Fiction</meta>
		<dc:subject id="subject-1">Horror tales</dc:subject>
		<meta property="authority" refines="#subject-1">LCSH</meta>
		<meta property="term" refines="#subject-1">sh85062084</meta>
		<meta property="se:subject">Horror</meta>
		<dc:description id="description">These are short fiction works of the genuinely curious character Algernon Blackwood, a prolific English writer mostly known for his deeply atmospheric, intensely human, and often quasi-autobiographical works of “weird fiction,” stories of the supernatural, paranormal, horror, the pagan, and the spiritual.</dc:description>
		<meta id="long-description" property="se:long-description" refines="#description">
			&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href="https://standardebooks.org/ebooks/algernon-blackwood"&gt;Algernon Blackwood&lt;/a&gt; was a prolific English writer, who published between 1899 and 1950. He is mostly known for his works of “weird fiction,” stories involving themes of the supernatural, paranormal, horror, the pagan, and the spiritual. His works tend to be deeply atmospheric, intensely human, and includes short fiction, plays, novels, and an autobiography. A genuinely curious character, much of Blackwood’s fiction is described as quasi-autobiographical. He left a substantial written legacy whose full extent is not known, Blackwood himself did know how many works he had published. Blackwood’s legacy also includes his influence on subsequent writers. His best known works are “The Wendigo” and “The Willows,” a novella described by Lovecraft as the finest supernatural tale in English literature. &lt;/p&gt;
		</meta>
